




TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Effect of Implicit Contracts on the Movement of Wages Over the Business Cycle: Evidence from Micro Data
AU  - Beaudry, Paul
AU  - DiNardo, John
Y1  - 1991/08/01
PY  - 1991
DA  - 1991/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/261774
DO  - 10.1086/261774
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 665
EP  - 688
VL  - 99
IS  - 4
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - In this paper we address the question of whether wages are affected by labor market conditions in a manner more consistent with a contract approach than with a standard spot market model. From a simple implicit contract model, we derive implications about the links between wages and past labor market conditions. Using individual data from the Current Population Survey and the Panel Study of Income Dynamics, we find that an implicit contract model with costless mobility describes these links better than either a simple spot market model or an implicit contract model with costly mobility.
AB  - In this paper we address the question of whether wages are affected by labor market conditions in a manner more consistent with a contract approach than with a standard spot market model. From a simple implicit contract model, we derive implications about the links between wages and past labor market conditions. Using individual data from the Current Population Survey and the Panel Study of Income Dynamics, we find that an implicit contract model with costless mobility describes these links better than either a simple spot market model or an implicit contract model with costly mobility.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/261774
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/261774
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Monitoring and Reputation: The Choice between Bank Loans and Directly Placed Debt
AU  - Diamond, Douglas W.
Y1  - 1991/08/01
PY  - 1991
DA  - 1991/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/261775
DO  - 10.1086/261775
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 689
EP  - 721
VL  - 99
IS  - 4
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This paper determines when a debt contract will be monitored by lenders. This is the choice between borrowing directly (issuing a bond, without monitoring) and borrowing through a bank that monitors to alleviate moral hazard. This provides a theory of bank loan demand and of the role of monitoring in circumstances in which reputation effects are important. A key result is that borrowers with credit ratings toward the middle of the spectrum rely on bank loans, and in periods of high interest rates or low future profitability, higher-rated borrowers choose to borrow from banks.
AB  - This paper determines when a debt contract will be monitored by lenders. This is the choice between borrowing directly (issuing a bond, without monitoring) and borrowing through a bank that monitors to alleviate moral hazard. This provides a theory of bank loan demand and of the role of monitoring in circumstances in which reputation effects are important. A key result is that borrowers with credit ratings toward the middle of the spectrum rely on bank loans, and in periods of high interest rates or low future profitability, higher-rated borrowers choose to borrow from banks.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/261775
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/261775
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Rational Addictive Behavior and Cigarette Smoking
AU  - Chaloupka, Frank
Y1  - 1991/08/01
PY  - 1991
DA  - 1991/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/261776
DO  - 10.1086/261776
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 722
EP  - 742
VL  - 99
IS  - 4
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Cigarette demand equations accounting for tolerance, reinforcement, and withdrawal are derived using the Becker-Murphy model of rational addiction and are estimated using data from the second National Health and Nutrition Examination Survey. Estimates imply that smoking is addictive, individuals are not myopic, and price increases would reduce demand. Implications concerning time preference and addiction are tested by estimating the demand separately for samples based on age and education. Less educated (younger) individuals are found to behave more myopically than more educated (older) individuals, whereas more addicted (myopic) individuals are found to respond more to price, in the long run, than less addicted (myopic) individuals.
AB  - Cigarette demand equations accounting for tolerance, reinforcement, and withdrawal are derived using the Becker-Murphy model of rational addiction and are estimated using data from the second National Health and Nutrition Examination Survey. Estimates imply that smoking is addictive, individuals are not myopic, and price increases would reduce demand. Implications concerning time preference and addiction are tested by estimating the demand separately for samples based on age and education. Less educated (younger) individuals are found to behave more myopically than more educated (older) individuals, whereas more addicted (myopic) individuals are found to respond more to price, in the long run, than less addicted (myopic) individuals.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/261776
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/261776
Y2  - 2024/03/22
